    <div xml:id="PN201">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>ivaryā reṉkuvai yāyi ṉivarē</l>
<l>yūruṭa ṉiravalark karuḷit tēruṭaṉ</l>
<l>mullaik kītta cellā nallicaip</l>
<l>paṭumaṇi yāṉaip paṟampiṟ kōmā</l>
<l>ṉeṭumāp pāri makaḷir yāṉē</l>
<l>tantai tōḻa ṉivareṉ makaḷi</l>
<l>rantaṇaṉ pulavaṉ koṇṭuvan taṉaṉē</l>
<l>nīyē vaṭapāṉ muṉivaṉ ṟaṭaviṉuṭ ṭōṉṟic</l>
<l>cempupuṉain tiyaṟṟiya cēṇeṭum puricai</l>
<l>yuvarā vīkait tuvarai yāṇṭu</l>
<l>nāṟpat toṉpatu vaḻimuṟai vanta</l>
<l>vēḷiruḷ vēḷē viṟaṟpō raṇṇa</l>
<l>ṟāraṇi yāṉaic cēṭṭiruṅ kōvē</l>
<l>yāṇkaṭa ṉuṭaimaiyiṟ pāṇkaṭa ṉāṟṟiya</l>
<l>voliyaṟ kaṇṇip pulikaṭi māal</l>
<l>yāṉṟara vivaraik koṇmati vāṉkavit</l>
<l>tiruṅkaṭa luṭuttaviv vaiyakat taruntiṟaṟ</l>
<l>poṉpaṭu mālvaraik kiḻava veṉvē</l>
<l>luṭaluna ruṭkun tāṉaik</l>
<l>keṭalaruṅ kuraiya nāṭukiḻa vōyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>If “you ask who are these [girls]?”, they (1)</l>
<l>are the daughters of tall great Pāri, (5a-c)</l>
<l>the king of Paṟampu hill with elephants with ringing bells, (4)</l>
<l>of fame that does not pass, who gave to a jasmine (3)</l>
<l>a chariot after at the same time(?) gracing supplicants with a village. (2)</l>
<l>	I, (5d)</l>
<l>I am a [their] father’s friend, they are [my] daughters. (6)</l>
<l>Taking [them] I, a brahmin, a scholar, have come. (7)</l>
<l>You, having appeared inside the sacrificial pit of the sage of the northern part, (8)</l>
<l>ruler among rulers (12ab)</l>
<l>who have come for forty-nine generations, (11)</l>
<l>ruling Dvāraka with unstinting generosity, (10)</l>
<l>[its] fortification tall in the distance which is made [and] fashioned from copper, (9)</l>
<l>	majesty of victorious battles, (12cd)</l>
<l>Iruṅkō, ???, with garland-adorned elephants, (13)</l>
<l>Pulikaṭimāal with a flourishing chaplet (15)</l>
<l>who, because there is a duty towards men, is able to [perform his] duty towards bards, (14)</l>
<l>while I give [them] you take them, (16a-c)</l>
<l>lord of the gold-yielding great mountain (18a-c)</l>
<l>of rare power in this world covered by the sky [and] encircled by the dark sea, (16d-17)</l>
<l>with a victorious spear [and] an army dreaded by those who angered [you], (18d-19)</l>
<l>lord of a land difficult to get lost. (20)</l>
</lg>
